segments.text: individuals, friends, and or faculty that were notable in your student days that if they were right here that you'd want to pat them on the back and thank them?
A lot of them, yes.
Who were they?
The names I told you earlier.
All right.
What about some, were there some close buddies?
Yeah.
I suspect I was very close to my roommate in college.
I told him the name of Harry Cordua.
Spell that.
C-O-R-D-U-A.
He was reared in Nicaragua, but he had American citizenship.
He was in Nicaragua when the Sandinistas killed him.
Now, how was he accepted as a student by the other students here?
Well, he had certain personality traits that sort of came through, and as a result they accepted him, but he was never in a really pushy, outgoing situation.
He struggled in his coursework somewhat.
He was not really the military type.
He never finished with OCS.

Let's make believe that someone today gave you a check for a million dollars and there was only one restriction on it that you had to pass it on to Texas A&M but you could decide the use of the million dollars.
What would you have A&M do with your gift of a million dollars?
Now you're bringing me up to date.
I think that I would give a million dollars.
I would like to see something in terms of the social sciences, not economics, not business.
more in the area of philosophy, history, and that might be ingrained into the College of Agriculture and Life Sciences, and find some way to do that.
Now, that probably means a chair.
Does anybody else do that now?
Any other ag school that you know of?
Anybody?
There are faculty members who are in positions of colleges of agriculture.
We had Paul Thompson.
Lost him because...
But somehow to fix that thing because...
Just when you do it as a dean or something else, it becomes, shall we use the term, ephemeral?
Okay, last question then of this about your student days.
What feelings do you hold for Texas A&M in your heart now?
Describe how you feel about A&M.
Well, most of my life has been spent here.
I think this is a wonderful place.
I think it has great opportunity.
I'd like to see its progress.
I have a great deal of affection for this university.
I don't use the terminology that a lot of people were doing at my age, you know, went through, this is the greatest place in the whole world.
No, it is not the greatest place in all the world.
But it is the greatest place, but it has been a place that has grown and developed from when I was here, it was a small undergraduate
program to a major significant factor in the economy of this country and in the lives of lots of people.
And it's that growth ability that I've seen through the years, the fact that it has climbed, maybe by its bootstraps,
But it's that ability that it has, that it's hired people like Haskell Monroe who left ways of doing it.
I don't know that I'm entirely comfortable with the direction it's going, but I have long decided that my age, the young people of this
just as long as they begin to see where we can go and what we can do.
And it's how do we find ways in which the land grant university is going to be entirely different from what it was back then.
The Land-Grant University has a significant factor was access.
Anybody could come.
If you could maintain that, it is a significant factor of service to people.
But again, I guess it's that good old Aggie confidence, self-confidence.
that I see possible here more than any other place except the larger, the more prestigious universities where they have this image and they can do this image.
Maybe we can build an image at Texas A&M and do the same thing.
I hope the people will do it.
That's my feeling of Texas A&M.
